    <!-- Topic 2: Animal Fibers -->
    <div id="topic2" class="topic">
        <h2>Topic 2: Animal Fibers</h2>
        <p>
            Animal fibers are protein-based and are typically derived from the hair or fur of animals. Common animal fibers include:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Angora:</strong> Derived from Angora goats and rabbits, these fibers are soft, fine, and lightweight. They are often used in winter clothing because they are seven times warmer than regular wool.</li>
            <li><strong>Camel Family (Alpaca, Llama, Camel, Vicuña):</strong> These fibers are lightweight, lustrous, and warm. Vicuña fibers are known for being the finest animal fibers in the world, making them rare and valuable.</li>
            <li><strong>Cashmere:</strong> Cashmere fibers, sourced from Kashmir goats, are soft and lightweight. They are commonly used in luxurious garments.</li>
            <li><strong>Wool:</strong> Wool is one of the most common animal fibers, derived from sheep. Wool has unique insulating properties, making it ideal for clothing in cold climates. In forensic investigations, wool can be identified by its surface structure, which contains scales, making it easy to differentiate under microscopic analysis.</li>
            <li><strong>Mohair:</strong> Derived from Angora goats, mohair fibers are durable, resilient, and lightweight. They are used in a variety of fashion and home décor items.</li>
            <li><strong>Silk:</strong> Produced by silkworms, silk fibers are renowned for their strength, shine, and smooth texture. In forensic science, silk fibers are unique due to their distinct molecular structure and high tensile strength, aiding in differentiation from other fiber types.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Special Type:</strong></p>
        <p>
            <strong>Marine Animal Fibers:</strong> Derived from fish or marine mammals, these fibers possess distinct properties compared to terrestrial animal fibers. They may exhibit unique surface textures and resilience due to their aquatic origins, presenting specialized forensic considerations.
        </p>
        <button onclick="showQuiz(2)">Take the quiz for Topic 2</button>
    </div>

