    <!-- Topic 3: Plant-Based Fibers -->
    <div id="topic3" class="topic">
        <h2>Topic 3: Plant-Based Fibers (Cellulosic Fibers)</h2>
        <p>
            Plant-based fibers are primarily made of cellulose, a complex carbohydrate found in plant cell walls. These fibers are used in various applications, from clothing to industrial products. Examples include:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Abacá:</strong> Known for its strength and durability, abacá fibers come from the stalks of the abacá plant and are used in products like ropes and specialty papers.</li>
            <li><strong>Coir:</strong> Extracted from the husks of coconuts, coir fibers are strong and resistant to moisture, making them suitable for products like doormats and mattresses.</li>
            <li><strong>Cotton:</strong> A highly absorbent and versatile fiber derived from the cotton plant, cotton is used in a wide range of textile products, including clothing, towels, and bed sheets.</li>
            <li><strong>Flax:</strong> Flax fibers are used to make linen, which is lightweight and absorbent. Flax fibers are strong and are primarily used in textile production.</li>
            <li><strong>Jute:</strong> Jute fibers are strong and durable, commonly used in the production of sacks, bags, and ropes.</li>
            <li><strong>Kapok:</strong> Kapok fibers are lightweight and buoyant, making them ideal for use in pillows and life jackets.</li>
            <li><strong>Kenaf:</strong> Derived from the kenaf plant, these fibers are used in paper production and other industrial applications.</li>
            <li><strong>Raffia:</strong> Raffia fibers are pliable and come from the leaves of the raffia palm. They are often used in the production of hats, baskets, and handicrafts.</li>
            <li><strong>Bamboo:</strong> Lightweight and flexible, bamboo fibers are used in textiles such as clothing and towels.</li>
            <li><strong>Hemp:</strong> Known for its strength and durability, hemp fibers are used in textiles, ropes, and paper products.</li>
            <li><strong>Modal:</strong> Made from beech trees, modal fibers are soft, lightweight, and often used in textiles like clothing and bedding.</li>
            <li><strong>Piña:</strong> Extracted from pineapple leaves, piña fibers are used in traditional Filipino textile production to create intricate fabrics.</li>
            <li><strong>Ramie:</strong> Ramie fibers, which come from the stems of the ramie plant, are strong and durable, commonly used in textiles and industrial materials.</li>
            <li><strong>Sisal:</strong> Recognized for its strength, sisal is often used to make ropes, carpets, and twine.</li>
            <li><strong>Soy Protein:</strong> These fibers are produced from tofu-manufacturing waste and are used as sustainable alternatives in textiles.</li>
            <li><strong>Seed Fibers:</strong> Including cotton and kapok, seed fibers have specific forensic relevance due to their distinct physical characteristics, such as fiber shape, surface texture, and tensile strength.</li>
            <li><strong>Hemp-Cotton Blends:</strong> Combining the durability of hemp with the softness of cotton, these blends are increasingly used in eco-friendly textiles, providing unique forensic identification markers.</li>
        </ul>
        <button onclick="showQuiz(3)">Take the quiz for Topic 3</button>
    </div>

