    <!-- Topic 4: Mineral-Based Fibers -->
    <div id="topic4" class="topic">
        <h2>Topic 4: Mineral-Based Fibers</h2>
        <p>
            Mineral-based fibers are derived from inorganic sources, such as minerals and metals. These fibers are less common in everyday textiles but are significant in specific industrial and specialized applications.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Asbestos:</strong> Known for its fire-resistant properties, asbestos was commonly used in heat-resistant applications before its health risks were recognized.</li>
            <li><strong>Fiberglass:</strong> Made from a combination of silicate minerals, fiberglass is used for its fire-resistant properties and is often found in insulation materials.</li>
            <li><strong>Metallic Fibers:</strong> These fibers can be made from metals such as gold, silver, copper, and aluminum or coated with metal. They are used for their conductivity and decorative qualities in textiles.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Additional Types:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Titanium Fibers:</strong> Utilized in high-strength applications, titanium fibers are noted for their corrosion resistance and lightweight properties.</li>
            <li><strong>Nickel Fibers:</strong> Employed in specialized industrial textiles, nickel fibers offer excellent tensile strength and thermal stability.</li>
        </ul>
        <button onclick="showQuiz(4)">Take the quiz for Topic 4</button>
    </div>

