    <!-- Topic 5: Synthetic Fibers -->
    <div id="topic5" class="topic">
        <h2>Topic 5: Synthetic Fibers</h2>
        <p>
            Synthetic fibers are man-made and are produced through chemical processes. They are widely used in modern textiles due to their durability and unique properties. Examples include:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Rayon (Viscose):</strong> A semi-synthetic fiber made from regenerated cellulose, rayon is highly absorbent and has a lustrous appearance.</li>
            <li><strong>Acetate:</strong> Another semi-synthetic fiber derived from cellulose, acetate is often used in clothing and upholstery due to its pliability and sheen.</li>
            <li><strong>Tencel:</strong> A lightweight fiber made from wood pulp, Tencel is highly breathable and comfortable to wear.</li>
            <li><strong>Polyester:</strong> A synthetic fiber made from polyethylene terephthalate, polyester is known for its wrinkle-resistant properties and ease of care.</li>
            <li><strong>Aramid:</strong> Aramid fibers are heat-resistant and strong, often used in bulletproof vests and aerospace materials.</li>
            <li><strong>Acrylic:</strong> Made from acrylonitrile, acrylic fibers mimic the properties of wool and are used in knitwear and faux fur products.</li>
            <li><strong>Ingeo:</strong> Derived from polylactide, Ingeo fibers wick away moisture and are often used in activewear.</li>
            <li><strong>Luminex:</strong> Luminex fibers emit light and are used in telecommunications and medical devices.</li>
            <li><strong>Lurex:</strong> A blend of polyamide and polyester, Lurex fibers have a metallic appearance and are used in decorative fabrics.</li>
            <li><strong>Lyocell:</strong> Known for its strength and softness, lyocell is a biodegradable cellulose fiber used in textiles like clothing and towels.</li>
            <li><strong>Nylon:</strong> A strong and durable polyamide fiber, nylon is used in a variety of products, from clothing to industrial materials.</li>
            <li><strong>Spandex (Lycra):</strong> A highly elastic fiber made from polyurethane, spandex is used in sportswear and swimwear.</li>
            <li><strong>Olefin:</strong> Made from polyethylene or polypropylene, olefin fibers are lightweight and resistant to moisture, making them ideal for outdoor apparel.</li>
            <li><strong>PLA Fiber (Polylactide):</strong> Lightweight and resistant to UV light, PLA fibers are used in sportswear and outdoor fabrics.</li>
            <li><strong>Polypropylene:</strong> Often referred to as olefin, polypropylene is used in a variety of applications including thermal underwear, carpets, and industrial fabrics.</li>
            <li><strong>PBT (Polybutylene Terephthalate):</strong> Similar to polyester, PBT fibers are used in sportswear and automotive textiles due to their high resilience and resistance to chemicals.</li>
            <li><strong>Polyurethane Fibers:</strong> Used in applications requiring elasticity, these fibers are integral to stretchable garments and medical textiles.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Blended Fibers:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Polyester-Cotton Blends (Poly-Cotton):</strong> Combining the durability of polyester with the comfort of cotton, these blends are common in various textiles and can present unique forensic challenges.</li>
            <li><strong>Wool-Synthetic Blends:</strong> Often used in outerwear, these blends exhibit characteristics of both wool and synthetic fibers, aiding in more precise fiber identification.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>High-Performance Synthetics:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Kevlar:</strong> A type of aramid fiber used in protective gear, Kevlar has specialized forensic applications due to its high strength and heat resistance.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Biodegradable and Eco-Friendly Fibers:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Biosynthetic Fibers:</strong> Such as those derived from algae or other sustainable sources, these fibers are gaining popularity and may present emerging forensic considerations.</li>
        </ul>
        <button onclick="showQuiz(5)">Take the quiz for Topic 5</button>
    </div>

